Now, of course, the music that you're hearing there.

250
00:13:57,503 --> 00:14:00,925
Chris Vrenna had produced this track for Doom 3.

251
00:14:01,525 --> 00:14:03,166
Now Chris is an incredible person.

252
00:14:03,206 --> 00:14:04,827
I've only spoken to Chris a couple of times,

253
00:14:04,887 --> 00:14:07,048
but his high level of music ability

254
00:14:07,128 --> 00:14:09,049
is only matched by his personality.

255
00:14:09,089 --> 00:14:10,590
He's a really, really wonderful person.

256
00:14:11,491 --> 00:14:13,392
And Chris, of course, played drums on Nine Inch Nails

257
00:14:13,432 --> 00:14:15,313
for many years and went on to play with Marilyn Manson

258
00:14:15,333 --> 00:14:16,013
and all that sort of stuff.

259
00:14:16,413 --> 00:14:17,194
Really, really great guy.

260
00:14:18,294 --> 00:14:20,195
But it was his experience with Nine Inch Nails

261
00:14:20,215 --> 00:14:21,096
that remembered something.

262
00:14:21,456 --> 00:14:23,297
I remembered that at one point, Nine Inch Nails

263
00:14:23,337 --> 00:14:24,298
toured with David Bowie.

264
00:14:26,149 --> 00:14:30,833
David Bowie himself is obviously a really incredible musician, and this reminded me of an interesting story.

265
00:14:38,798 --> 00:14:47,805
Back in 1977, when Bowie was in Berlin recording Heroes, he was working with a fascinating engineer named Tony Visconti.

266
00:14:49,415 --> 00:14:52,337
Now, due to the technical limitations that these guys were working with,

267
00:14:52,778 --> 00:14:56,721
they'd pretty much run out with tracks on this tape machine that they were using.

268
00:14:57,182 --> 00:14:58,883
They had one track left for vocals.

269
00:14:59,684 --> 00:15:02,246
But to get the full emotional impact of this song across,

270
00:15:02,586 --> 00:15:04,648
they needed to have reverb that was scalable.

271
00:15:05,689 --> 00:15:08,772
So Tony, the engineer, came up with this really incredible technique.

272
00:15:10,033 --> 00:15:12,915
He set up David Bowie in the middle of the studio here, right at the frontier.

273
00:15:13,616 --> 00:15:15,558
So David would be singing into that microphone.

274
00:15:17,005 --> 00:15:19,747
About 20 feet away from that would be a second microphone.

275
00:15:21,067 --> 00:15:23,669
Then at the end of the hall was a third microphone.

276
00:15:25,010 --> 00:15:27,031
Now, microphones two and three at the back

277
00:15:27,091 --> 00:15:28,591
there were behind a gate.

278
00:15:29,272 --> 00:15:30,613
Everybody understands what a gate is, right?

279
00:15:30,673 --> 00:15:32,013
Open, close gate, audio gate, right?

280
00:15:34,355 --> 00:15:36,896
Now, when David was singing at the start of the song,

281
00:15:37,296 --> 00:15:38,917
and it was kind of low tones, there

282
00:15:38,957 --> 00:15:40,438
wasn't much volume to his voice.

283
00:15:40,858 --> 00:15:42,779
So this first microphone was all that was picking up.

284
00:15:44,174 --> 00:15:47,096
Then when he'd open up a little bit, the second microphone,

285
00:15:47,136 --> 00:15:49,278
the gate would open and allow some of his voice through.

286
00:15:49,698 --> 00:15:51,640
That would create a bit of a natural ambience.

287
00:15:52,881 --> 00:15:55,023
Then when Bowie would really rip into it,

288
00:15:55,363 --> 00:15:57,565
the gate on the third microphone at the back would open up.

289
00:15:59,266 --> 00:16:01,147
And what I thought was really fascinating about this

290
00:16:01,908 --> 00:16:05,551
is that they designed a system that dynamically added

291
00:16:05,671 --> 00:16:07,953
reverb based on the input.

292
00:16:10,835 --> 00:16:12,736
So I thought, well, what if I designed a system

293
00:16:14,394 --> 00:16:17,476
that dynamically produced interesting and appropriate musical bits

294
00:16:18,797 --> 00:16:19,638
based on the input.

295
00:16:22,520 --> 00:16:25,983
To be inspired by this, I started getting this awesome concept art through for the

296
00:16:26,003 --> 00:16:26,443
project.

297
00:16:27,263 --> 00:16:28,644
I was really fascinated by these

298
00:16:29,265 --> 00:16:32,948
concepts of where they had these giant rock structures that were being held

299
00:16:33,008 --> 00:16:33,688
together with this

300
00:16:34,168 --> 00:16:36,290
evil force of energy, this hell energy.

301
00:16:37,415 --> 00:16:40,558
And the story in the game is that this evil corporation

302
00:16:40,978 --> 00:16:43,020
has found a way to mine this energy

303
00:16:43,621 --> 00:16:45,402
as a source of renewable energy, right?

304
00:16:45,442 --> 00:16:46,623
Sustainable energy source.

305
00:16:47,604 --> 00:16:49,026
But I kind of love this idea

306
00:16:49,366 --> 00:16:51,107
that everything from your mobile phone

307
00:16:51,628 --> 00:16:52,809
to the TV you watch,

308
00:16:53,270 --> 00:16:54,971
to the pacemaker that's keeping you alive,

309
00:16:55,311 --> 00:16:56,533
to the plane that you're flying,

310
00:16:57,253 --> 00:17:00,056
is all being powered by energy mined from hell.

311
00:17:00,736 --> 00:17:02,018
It's kind of evil energy, right?

312
00:17:03,233 --> 00:17:08,535
I had this idea about this sort of force that was traveling through things and getting corrupted,

313
00:17:09,135 --> 00:17:09,975
this evil energy.

314
00:17:11,515 --> 00:17:14,956
So with that in mind, I set out to design the following system.

315
00:17:18,457 --> 00:17:23,678
Now for the sake of this next bit, I want you to think of audio like water.

316
00:17:24,938 --> 00:17:26,339
It flows downhill.

317
00:17:28,479 --> 00:17:29,920
We start with a computer at the top.

318
00:17:31,445 --> 00:17:33,206
The computer is what generates the sound.

319
00:17:33,406 --> 00:17:35,767
In this case, it was a simple sine wave.

320
00:17:36,187 --> 00:17:37,708
We'll go into more of that in a little bit.

321
00:17:39,408 --> 00:17:41,789
That computer split that signal out

322
00:17:41,809 --> 00:17:43,250
into four different paths.

323
00:17:44,570 --> 00:17:46,551
These paths went into a chain.

324
00:17:47,931 --> 00:17:51,232
The first chain consisted of a whole bunch of pedals,

325
00:17:51,813 --> 00:17:52,773
four pedals as a result.

326
00:17:53,213 --> 00:17:55,174
Now, for this first test, I actually wrote these down

327
00:17:55,214 --> 00:17:57,095
for the real geeks in the audience, if you're curious.

328
00:17:58,354 --> 00:18:02,337
So the first pedal there was a Retro Mechanical Labs 432K

329
00:18:02,357 --> 00:18:04,439
distortion box, really, really great distortion box.

330
00:18:05,280 --> 00:18:07,782
The second pedal was a Metasonix KV100,

331
00:18:08,122 --> 00:18:09,583
really interesting tube distortion.

332
00:18:10,784 --> 00:18:12,346
The third pedal was a Geiger counter,

333
00:18:12,366 --> 00:18:13,907
it's like a bit crusher that you can kind of do

334
00:18:13,947 --> 00:18:14,768
some cool stuff with.

335
00:18:15,508 --> 00:18:17,971
The fourth pedal was a DwarfCraft fuzz

336
00:18:18,051 --> 00:18:19,892
from the DwarfCraft devices guys,

337
00:18:19,912 --> 00:18:20,933
they're really, really cool as well.

338
00:18:21,954 --> 00:18:22,855
That was the first chain.

339
00:18:23,535 --> 00:18:24,876
At the bottom of that was a splitter,

340
00:18:24,977 --> 00:18:26,178
we'll get back to that one in a second.

341
00:18:27,727 --> 00:18:30,069
The second chain went through a very similar setup.

342
00:18:30,109 --> 00:18:31,330
We had another four pedals.

343
00:18:31,390 --> 00:18:33,311
The first one was another Geiger counter,

344
00:18:33,431 --> 00:18:34,112
just for awesomeness.

345
00:18:34,953 --> 00:18:37,034
The second one was a Metasonic's TX3.

346
00:18:37,235 --> 00:18:38,015
Google it or don't.

347
00:18:39,436 --> 00:18:41,098
The third was a Mutron Bi-Phase,

348
00:18:41,138 --> 00:18:44,581
an old phaser from like the late 60s, early 70s,

349
00:18:44,661 --> 00:18:45,702
really, really old phaser pedal.

350
00:18:45,722 --> 00:18:48,284
And because I really liked old phaser pedals,

351
00:18:48,304 --> 00:18:49,305
there was a second one of those.

352
00:18:49,385 --> 00:18:51,066
It was a Dodd 70s phaser as well.

353
00:18:51,787 --> 00:18:52,667
So really, really cool stuff.

354
00:18:54,129 --> 00:18:55,310
At the end of that was a compressor.

355
00:18:55,330 --> 00:18:56,711
We'll come back to that one in a second.

356
00:18:57,849 --> 00:18:59,952
The third chain consisted of a tape echo.

357
00:18:59,972 --> 00:19:03,077
I had this Watkins Copycat old tape echo.

358
00:19:03,377 --> 00:19:04,979
They would actually record to a tape,

359
00:19:05,300 --> 00:19:07,183
and then the record head is back with the play head,

360
00:19:07,243 --> 00:19:08,885
so whatever you record plays up behind.

361
00:19:08,925 --> 00:19:10,888
And that's like proper echo, actual natural echo

362
00:19:10,909 --> 00:19:12,271
when they're on a tape machine, right?

363
00:19:12,331 --> 00:19:12,711
Real stuff.

364
00:19:14,005 --> 00:19:18,266
The second distortion box that was under that, the pedal one that you see listed there on the third chain,

365
00:19:18,286 --> 00:19:21,967
that was just another distortion box, it was a Trogatronic valve distortion thing.

366
00:19:22,567 --> 00:19:26,428
It wasn't really there for the distortion aspect, it was there more for the compression aspect.

367
00:19:27,168 --> 00:19:31,129
After that I had this old Akai reel-to-reel machine from the 70s.

368
00:19:32,149 --> 00:19:35,310
It's like a tiny little quarter inch thing, great sound, really really grimy.

369
00:19:36,010 --> 00:19:39,451
What I was doing here was feeding it with about 40 decibels more than it could handle,

370
00:19:39,811 --> 00:19:43,251
which was really really cool, and then recording back off it at the same time.

371
00:19:44,132 --> 00:19:48,500
Following on to that, that went into a spring reverb tank with a wet and dry control so

372
00:19:48,520 --> 00:19:49,823
I could kind of play around with that.

373
00:19:50,224 --> 00:19:52,307
That went into a compressor, which I'll talk about in a second.

374
00:19:53,370 --> 00:19:55,751
The final one we did a couple of different interesting things with.

375
00:19:56,131 --> 00:19:57,972
The signal was sent out to a little mini amp.

376
00:19:57,992 --> 00:20:00,092
You know those little crappy Fender mini amp things

377
00:20:00,112 --> 00:20:01,473
that got a tiny little speaker in them?

378
00:20:02,873 --> 00:20:04,894
Again, it was being fed with about 40 decibels too much

379
00:20:04,914 --> 00:20:05,634
of what it can handle.

380
00:20:07,135 --> 00:20:10,836
That was being mic'd with a little microphone.

381
00:20:11,036 --> 00:20:13,636
So the speaker had a microphone in front of it.

382
00:20:13,937 --> 00:20:15,477
And a little bit of that signal was

383
00:20:15,497 --> 00:20:18,278
being sent through a splitter back into the amp itself.

384
00:20:18,338 --> 00:20:19,938
So we're creating a feedback loop there.

385
00:20:21,208 --> 00:20:23,369
But the feedback loop was only very, very small.

386
00:20:23,409 --> 00:20:25,790
It was so small that if a sound was actually

387
00:20:25,830 --> 00:20:28,172
coming through the amp, it would choke out the feedback.

388
00:20:28,592 --> 00:20:30,513
And when that sound started to disappear,

389
00:20:30,773 --> 00:20:32,554
the feedback would come back up in the mix.

390
00:20:32,954 --> 00:20:34,475
I have a little example of that running here.

391
00:20:41,959 --> 00:20:43,820
So we can hear whenever that distortion sort of stuff

392
00:20:43,840 --> 00:20:45,581
starts to die out, the feedback comes in, right?

393
00:20:47,762 --> 00:20:50,484
So the next thing is that every single one of those

394
00:20:50,564 --> 00:20:53,426
ran into a mixer, so I can start summing things back down.

395
00:20:54,387 --> 00:20:56,269
That ran into an EQ and a compressor.

396
00:20:56,589 --> 00:20:58,130
The EQ wasn't really doing much.

397
00:20:58,170 --> 00:21:00,632
It was adding about four or five decibels down really low,

398
00:21:00,672 --> 00:21:01,974
about 30 to 60 hertz.

399
00:21:02,374 --> 00:21:04,636
And then we're adding about the same up, about sort of 8 to 10,

400
00:21:05,096 --> 00:21:07,518
basically creating a nice sort of smiley face EQ.

401
00:21:07,578 --> 00:21:08,699
Nothing really amazing there.

402
00:21:09,680 --> 00:21:11,101
That was running into a compressor.

403
00:21:11,361 --> 00:21:13,443
This compressor was absolutely friggin' pinned.

404
00:21:13,963 --> 00:21:15,944
I'm kidding, it was knocking off about 20 decibels.

405
00:21:17,065 --> 00:21:19,027
The reason I was hitting it that hard

406
00:21:19,467 --> 00:21:23,130
was so when the loud noises would start to go away,

407
00:21:23,530 --> 00:21:25,251
the compressor would begin to open up

408
00:21:25,571 --> 00:21:27,653
and bring up all the interesting noise

409
00:21:28,153 --> 00:21:30,635
that every single one of these pedals and bits of equipment was creating.

410
00:21:30,935 --> 00:21:32,977
I'll show you more of that in a second, that's very important.

411
00:21:33,577 --> 00:21:36,359
The compressor itself was set at about a 30 millisecond attack,

412
00:21:36,639 --> 00:21:38,060
so we got some really cool punchy stuff.

413
00:21:38,360 --> 00:21:39,901
And then I'd adjust the release based

414
00:21:39,941 --> 00:21:41,622
on the tempo of whatever I was sending through it.

415
00:21:41,942 --> 00:21:43,543
Again, I'll show you that more in a second.

416
00:21:44,164 --> 00:21:45,945
The ratio was about 12 or 20 to 1.

417
00:21:46,045 --> 00:21:47,305
Pretty, pretty, pretty drastic.

418
00:21:47,386 --> 00:21:47,866
Pretty crazy.

419
00:21:49,047 --> 00:21:51,808
And that was running straight into the digital audio workstation

420
00:21:51,848 --> 00:21:52,689
there and recording stuff.

421
00:21:53,249 --> 00:21:55,530
So what I'm going to do next is attempt

422
00:21:55,570 --> 00:21:58,172
to, if we can get some volume on the computer here,

423
00:21:59,308 --> 00:22:04,611
I'm going to show you my first experiment running through this array.

424
00:22:05,552 --> 00:22:09,093
I'm going to show you a series of sub sine wave tones.

425
00:22:09,774 --> 00:22:12,855
They're four F notes followed by a little bit of a gap.

426
00:22:28,955 --> 00:22:29,995
Okay, so that's it.

427
00:22:30,055 --> 00:22:30,796
Now I know what you're thinking,

428
00:22:30,836 --> 00:22:31,796
it's really not amazing, right?

429
00:22:31,836 --> 00:22:33,257
I know, music of the year right here, woo!

430
00:22:37,079 --> 00:22:40,982
But when you run that through this array,

431
00:22:41,982 --> 00:22:44,223
all sorts of interesting stuff starts to happen.

432
00:22:46,345 --> 00:22:48,446
What I want you to listen out for is a couple of things.

433
00:22:49,727 --> 00:22:51,708
At the end of those four F notes,

434
00:22:52,008 --> 00:22:53,989
you'll hear another note creep in underneath.

435
00:22:54,770 --> 00:22:56,651
It's like an E, it's like just below the F.

436
00:22:57,527 --> 00:23:00,569
That's not being generated from me, that's not being generated from the computer,

437
00:23:00,849 --> 00:23:03,091
that's coming from some ground hum within the array.

438
00:23:04,132 --> 00:23:07,974
Additional to that, there's all sorts of interesting distortion layers that are coming in and out

439
00:23:08,695 --> 00:23:10,916
based on that splitter on the left-hand side there

440
00:23:11,277 --> 00:23:13,858
that was sending a signal to those compressors along the bottom.

441
00:23:15,099 --> 00:23:20,183
Sometimes, if I wanted to, that was essentially sidechaining the signal from those other chains.

442
00:23:21,237 --> 00:23:25,359
So based on whatever the input was doing,

443
00:23:25,700 --> 00:23:29,863
it could dynamically change the mix of each chain I had.

444
00:23:32,324 --> 00:23:33,385
The last thing I want you to hear out

445
00:23:33,405 --> 00:23:34,646
for is all sorts of interesting stuff

446
00:23:34,666 --> 00:23:36,027
that's going on with the sonics and things.

447
00:23:36,047 --> 00:23:37,268
You'll hear all sorts of harmonics.

448
00:23:38,028 --> 00:23:41,391
Anyway, here again is that same subwoofer tone run

449
00:23:41,411 --> 00:23:42,751
through this array several times.

450
00:24:31,584 --> 00:24:33,245
Now we're getting somewhere interesting.

451
00:24:33,265 --> 00:24:40,731
So the way I started thinking about this

452
00:24:41,231 --> 00:24:42,792
was that this was my instrument.

453
00:24:44,193 --> 00:24:46,314
I'm feeding it a very basic input,

454
00:24:47,295 --> 00:24:49,216
and all I'm changing from that input

455
00:24:49,617 --> 00:24:52,459
is amplitude and pitch of what I'm sending through.

456
00:24:53,339 --> 00:24:55,401
Everything I was sending through, it was a sine wave.

457
00:24:55,861 --> 00:24:56,341
That's it.

458
00:24:57,975 --> 00:25:00,697
The reason I chose a sine wave is because a sine wave

459
00:25:00,797 --> 00:25:03,960
is our most pure representation of what sound can be.

460
00:25:05,362 --> 00:25:06,843
It's simply a wave that goes up

461
00:25:07,263 --> 00:25:08,464
and a wave that comes back down.

462
00:25:09,846 --> 00:25:12,588
Therefore, any interesting thing that was happening

463
00:25:12,648 --> 00:25:16,892
within this array was being imparted onto that sine wave

464
00:25:17,293 --> 00:25:18,714
in the purest form possible.

465
00:25:19,595 --> 00:25:22,337
I started to think about this as my doom instrument.

466
00:25:23,465 --> 00:25:25,587
Now, don't care too much about this sort of thing.

467
00:25:25,627 --> 00:25:26,588
These pedals would change.

468
00:25:26,628 --> 00:25:28,289
I'd swap stuff out and all that sort of thing.

469
00:25:28,529 --> 00:25:29,990
But the concept remained the same.

470
00:25:30,010 --> 00:25:32,372
I'm going to show you a couple more examples of what

471
00:25:32,392 --> 00:25:33,233
I ran through it next.

472
00:25:33,793 --> 00:25:35,415
Here's another little sub part I ran through.

473
00:25:35,455 --> 00:25:36,275
I hope you guys can hear it.

474
00:25:40,258 --> 00:25:40,659
That's it.

475
00:25:40,899 --> 00:25:41,800
Very, very interesting.

476
00:25:41,840 --> 00:25:42,180
Not really.

477
00:25:42,220 --> 00:25:42,760
Kind of sucks.

478
00:25:43,121 --> 00:25:44,742
Here it is run through that array.

479
00:25:45,142 --> 00:25:47,144
All I'm doing is changing the amplitude

480
00:25:47,364 --> 00:25:49,065
and then tweaking some of the knobs as I go.

481
00:26:16,815 --> 00:26:17,776
Here's another example.

482
00:26:17,856 --> 00:26:18,896
This is the same sort of thing.

