00:28:22,979 --> 00:28:23,960
it was kind of special to do,

500
00:28:23,980 --> 00:28:25,562
and it started feeling really, really good.

501
00:28:25,982 --> 00:28:26,803
Throwing it in the game,

502
00:28:26,863 --> 00:28:28,606
everybody was responding to it really well.

503
00:28:29,126 --> 00:28:30,248
We were really quite happy with it.

504
00:28:31,289 --> 00:28:34,533
The thing was though, it was missing something.

505
00:28:38,520 --> 00:28:41,685
See, the modern Doom is nothing but a tribute to 90s game design.

506
00:28:42,345 --> 00:28:44,008
90s game design is really quite fascinating.

507
00:28:44,328 --> 00:28:46,191
You walk into a room and you're instantly

508
00:28:46,231 --> 00:28:48,874
presented with a series of very distinguishable enemies.

509
00:28:49,535 --> 00:28:52,519
It's your job, then, to figure out what weapon you want to pick

510
00:28:52,779 --> 00:28:54,542
to be able to kind of get rid of those enemies.

511
00:28:55,162 --> 00:28:58,425
Now it's for that reason that you're allowed to carry as many weapons as you like.

512
00:28:58,785 --> 00:29:02,187
You don't need to aim down the sights, you're not hiding behind cover, none of this sort

513
00:29:02,227 --> 00:29:02,608
of stuff.

514
00:29:03,108 --> 00:29:05,990
The idea is that you're being constantly encouraged to move.

515
00:29:06,430 --> 00:29:07,171
It's very quick.

516
00:29:07,571 --> 00:29:08,672
It's very fast.

517
00:29:09,413 --> 00:29:13,115
In fact, even when you start to take health, you've got to go look for a health pack.

518
00:29:13,375 --> 00:29:15,297
You can't just hide somewhere and have it generate.

519
00:29:15,677 --> 00:29:17,699
It's all about kind of keeping that moving, right?

520
00:29:18,439 --> 00:29:22,161
Now I feel that what was really interesting about the Doom team on the new Doom

521
00:29:22,421 --> 00:29:25,082
was that we were really able to capture that 90s feeling

522
00:29:25,682 --> 00:29:28,043
even with a modern first-person shooter.

523
00:29:30,344 --> 00:29:32,445
When I visited the id Studios in Dallas,

524
00:29:32,665 --> 00:29:36,847
I was really blown away with how well the new Doom game actually felt.

525
00:29:37,348 --> 00:29:42,290
It was making me get these sort of weird nostalgic feelings of playing Doom back in the day.

526
00:29:42,310 --> 00:29:44,691
It was feeling very, very similar to the same thing.

527
00:29:45,919 --> 00:29:48,641
So the game itself there felt like Doom,

528
00:29:50,342 --> 00:29:52,523
but it wasn't sounding like Doom.

529
00:29:53,964 --> 00:29:55,305
And I knew exactly why.

530
00:30:01,449 --> 00:30:02,630
We had no guitars.

531
00:30:05,752 --> 00:30:07,793
Now, of course, there's a really good reason behind that, right?

532
00:30:08,153 --> 00:30:10,014
I mean, I know they said no guitars, we hate guitars,

533
00:30:10,034 --> 00:30:11,015
don't put guitars into a game.

534
00:30:11,055 --> 00:30:12,516
But I totally understood why.

535
00:30:13,196 --> 00:30:13,436
Why?

536
00:30:15,123 --> 00:30:17,225
It's because the sound of an electric guitar

537
00:30:17,865 --> 00:30:20,827
somehow instantly summarizes a genre

538
00:30:21,547 --> 00:30:23,128
that has become a bit of a joke.

539
00:30:23,608 --> 00:30:25,149
So I'll pick one up when I go out today.

540
00:30:25,649 --> 00:30:27,050
Other than that, I'm a good chick.

541
00:30:55,240 --> 00:30:57,141
So I mean, you can instantly see why.

542
00:30:57,161 --> 00:31:00,905
No developer wants to be associated with such a joke, right?

543
00:31:00,985 --> 00:31:02,306
I mean, it totally makes sense.

544
00:31:03,587 --> 00:31:10,493
The thing is, though, that harsh, aggressive, up-front sound that you get from a guitar

545
00:31:11,374 --> 00:31:15,718
is exactly appropriate, and it was the thing that was missing from the soundtrack.

546
00:31:16,909 --> 00:31:19,370
Now it took some convincing, but after a while

547
00:31:19,410 --> 00:31:21,630
we started looking at, hey, what happens

548
00:31:21,670 --> 00:31:24,191
if we add a little bit of guitar, like 5% here,

549
00:31:24,771 --> 00:31:26,331
and then maybe 10% here, right?

550
00:31:26,391 --> 00:31:27,311
Little bit by little bit.

551
00:31:27,351 --> 00:31:28,592
No, slowly, slowly, slowly.

552
00:31:29,632 --> 00:31:31,792
What we wanted to do, though, was kind of experiment

553
00:31:31,832 --> 00:31:33,213
with different guitar tones.

554
00:31:33,733 --> 00:31:36,333
We didn't just want to take sort of general metal sounds

555
00:31:36,393 --> 00:31:37,694
and put those into the game, because it

556
00:31:37,734 --> 00:31:38,714
didn't feel appropriate.

557
00:31:38,994 --> 00:31:40,174
It kind of felt like that.

558
00:31:41,935 --> 00:31:43,615
So we started experimenting with different ways

559
00:31:43,655 --> 00:31:44,655
to get guitar tones.

560
00:31:46,798 --> 00:31:50,921
I was again inspired by the work that Chris Renner and things had done in the 90s and

561
00:31:50,941 --> 00:31:56,424
stuff like that and specifically Marilyn Manson and an engineer that Marilyn Manson worked

562
00:31:56,464 --> 00:31:57,505
with named Sean Bevan.

563
00:31:58,185 --> 00:32:03,209
And he had this brilliant technique back in the day of getting this really chunky guitar

564
00:32:03,249 --> 00:32:03,509
tone.

565
00:32:03,849 --> 00:32:07,111
And it was a guitar tone that they used for like beautiful people and stuff like that.

566
00:32:07,772 --> 00:32:11,814
And one of the methods they used to get that guitar tune was to take the guitar part as

567
00:32:11,874 --> 00:32:15,797
it normally was, play it up an octave and then twice as fast.

568
00:32:17,302 --> 00:32:20,805
And you'd record that to tape at 30 inches per second.

569
00:32:22,426 --> 00:32:24,268
Then you'd take that tape and slow it down

570
00:32:24,308 --> 00:32:26,970
to 15 inches per second and get some really interesting

571
00:32:27,010 --> 00:32:27,390
results.

572
00:32:28,591 --> 00:32:30,573
Now, I had a tape machine, and I wanted to give this a try.

573
00:32:31,213 --> 00:32:33,876
So this is the guitar part played up an octave twice

574
00:32:33,896 --> 00:32:34,376
as fast.

575
00:32:41,022 --> 00:32:42,423
Now, I know it sounds like Bill and Ted at the moment.

576
00:32:42,463 --> 00:32:42,843
Don't worry.

577
00:32:44,842 --> 00:32:49,967
We record that to tape at 30 inches per second, play it back at 15 inches per second, run

578
00:32:50,007 --> 00:32:53,111
it through a preamp which is kind of jacked pretty hard, you get this.

579
00:33:00,239 --> 00:33:02,461
Pretty cool stuff, super super gnarly right?

580
00:33:04,740 --> 00:33:08,982
Another thing I did was started extending the range of the guitar down a lot.

581
00:33:09,342 --> 00:33:12,383
Now, I know a lot of people have made jokes about this sort of thing, and fair enough,

582
00:33:12,463 --> 00:33:12,683
too.

583
00:33:13,403 --> 00:33:15,384
I got a hold of a nine string, right?

584
00:33:16,784 --> 00:33:18,345
Nine strings are really freaking crazy.

585
00:33:18,365 --> 00:33:19,485
You don't need a nine string.

586
00:33:19,545 --> 00:33:20,606
It's like excessiveness.

587
00:33:21,046 --> 00:33:25,347
A nine string is so low, it is literally like having a five string bass on the bottom of

588
00:33:25,387 --> 00:33:26,448
your regular guitar.

589
00:33:26,808 --> 00:33:27,748
It's kind of stupid.

590
00:33:31,009 --> 00:33:34,030
I had this nine string riff for the main menu theme.

591
00:33:43,941 --> 00:33:46,461
The trouble was that it was sounding too much like a guitar.

592
00:33:46,481 --> 00:33:48,762
It was sounding again too much like a sort of metal thing.

593
00:33:49,102 --> 00:33:50,782
And as I said, the whole nine string thing,

594
00:33:51,062 --> 00:33:52,903
yeah, really, really, really stupid.

595
00:33:53,283 --> 00:33:56,163
I actually got rid of the nine string after finishing up the Doom project.

596
00:33:56,203 --> 00:33:57,284
I gave it to a buddy of mine.

597
00:33:57,344 --> 00:34:01,124
He plays in like the biggest, most aggressive metal band in the world,

598
00:34:01,545 --> 00:34:03,185
and even he can't find a use for it.

599
00:34:05,785 --> 00:34:08,026
Around the time I was experimenting with this,

600
00:34:09,105 --> 00:34:14,088
The Zynaptic plugin people re-released a plugin called Morph.

601
00:34:15,188 --> 00:34:16,149
And it's a really cool plugin.

602
00:34:16,169 --> 00:34:17,230
I recommend anybody check it out.

603
00:34:17,270 --> 00:34:19,311
Basically what you can do is take two sounds

604
00:34:20,231 --> 00:34:22,133
and interpolate some characteristics

605
00:34:22,193 --> 00:34:23,493
of one sound into another.

606
00:34:23,914 --> 00:34:25,314
I don't know exactly how it works,

607
00:34:25,355 --> 00:34:26,815
but basically you can take one sound

608
00:34:26,855 --> 00:34:28,937
and kind of start to morph it into the other sound.

609
00:34:30,518 --> 00:34:33,720
I took a sample of the chainsaw from the original Doom game.

610
00:34:35,508 --> 00:34:40,051
and started to interpolate that guitar tone with that chainsaw sound.

611
00:34:40,552 --> 00:34:41,713
And this is what we ended up with.

612
00:35:01,394 --> 00:35:03,235
Doom's kind of violent if I didn't make that point.

613
00:35:04,675 --> 00:35:05,995
Sorry, I should have pointed that out at the beginning.

614
00:35:07,656 --> 00:35:09,056
Anyway, so this was a really interesting way

615
00:35:09,076 --> 00:35:11,677
to start getting some unique guitar tones into the game.

616
00:35:12,677 --> 00:35:14,697
Now, once I got this, I felt this

617
00:35:14,757 --> 00:35:17,018
was like the little Trojan horse that I

618
00:35:17,058 --> 00:35:19,679
was able to sneak into the id software bases, right?

619
00:35:20,339 --> 00:35:22,219
And once I was in there, I was able to put

620
00:35:22,259 --> 00:35:23,580
as much guitar in as I wanted.

621
00:35:26,679 --> 00:35:31,063
Interestingly, what that allowed us to do was do something that I really love doing

622
00:35:31,123 --> 00:35:32,304
on every single project.

623
00:35:32,865 --> 00:35:39,010
And that is to create a couple of songs that belong in the game that kind of become easily

624
00:35:39,091 --> 00:35:40,632
identifiable to that game.

625
00:35:40,992 --> 00:35:42,373
It's a process I really enjoy doing.

626
00:35:42,613 --> 00:35:44,915
It's not just like the score stuff that sits in the background,

627
00:35:45,235 --> 00:35:47,957
but it's these songs that fans seem to really enjoy.

628
00:35:47,997 --> 00:35:49,198
It's the ones that they point out with.

629
00:35:49,258 --> 00:35:51,659
It's the songs that become associated with the game in the end.

630
00:35:52,380 --> 00:35:54,561
So once we started doing this guitar thing,

631
00:35:54,901 --> 00:35:56,282
it allowed us to do this.

632
00:35:56,342 --> 00:35:58,063
It allowed us to get these songs in there.

633
00:35:58,384 --> 00:36:00,625
It was finally starting to feel like a Doom game,

634
00:36:00,885 --> 00:36:03,487
and not so much just like some nerdy, geeky synth-fest.

635
00:36:19,370 --> 00:36:21,772
So all of a sudden, just by adding that stuff in there,

636
00:36:22,073 --> 00:36:24,114
it started to feel like a Doom game.

637
00:36:24,815 --> 00:36:27,978
It started to make the player run around the arena a little bit

638
00:36:28,018 --> 00:36:29,920
more and feel comfortable doing that.

639
00:36:31,201 --> 00:36:32,962
Also, what was really funny about that

640
00:36:33,423 --> 00:36:36,045
is that once the game came out, fans of the game

641
00:36:36,325 --> 00:36:37,746
started to make jokes about the song.

642
00:37:08,311 --> 00:37:09,051
So there we go.

643
00:37:10,472 --> 00:37:13,694
By changing our process, we changed the outcome.

644
00:37:14,414 --> 00:37:17,436
We were able to come up with some sounds that fit the game.

645
00:37:17,456 --> 00:37:19,277
I would argue that it's not stuff

646
00:37:19,317 --> 00:37:21,178
that nobody's ever heard before, but it

647
00:37:21,218 --> 00:37:23,800
was something that started to become quite unique for Doom.

648
00:37:25,057 --> 00:37:26,177
It fit the project.

649
00:37:26,978 --> 00:37:28,798
By adding a bit of guitar and stuff in there,

650
00:37:28,878 --> 00:37:30,999
it started to fit the project even further.

651
00:37:31,759 --> 00:37:33,619
Even that was in the brief as a no-no,

652
00:37:34,139 --> 00:37:36,520
we decided to go back and change that brief

653
00:37:36,880 --> 00:37:39,440
in order to better kind of access that other point

654
00:37:39,480 --> 00:37:40,301
that was in the brief,

655
00:37:41,041 --> 00:37:43,521
which was that it needs to be instantly loved

656
00:37:43,581 --> 00:37:46,022
by all the Doom fans out in the world, right?

