I would send the signal out,

1015
00:52:50,750 --> 00:52:53,291
and I'd set the attack so it would be, say,

1016
00:52:53,691 --> 00:52:54,591
.3 or 30, whatever it is, 30.

1017
00:52:55,171 --> 00:52:56,292
So yeah, 30 milliseconds.

1018
00:52:56,632 --> 00:52:57,792
And that usually creates a really,

1019
00:52:57,812 --> 00:52:59,032
really nice and sharp attack.

1020
00:52:59,412 --> 00:53:03,796
And then everything was running through a slow compressor at the end that was really pinning things back like that.

1021
00:53:04,677 --> 00:53:09,702
Once that came into the computer, I might do some more processing within the computer itself,

1022
00:53:09,742 --> 00:53:14,606
such as transient processing and things like that, just to kind of get those transients really to punch through.

1023
00:53:15,207 --> 00:53:19,030
Transients, I believe, are really the key to getting a really punchy sounding game mix.

1024
00:53:19,550 --> 00:53:23,253
When you've got all these sound effects and screams and gunshots and all this sort of stuff going through,

1025
00:53:23,573 --> 00:53:27,856
if you've got just a solidly limited thing sitting in the background, it doesn't come through.

1026
00:53:28,156 --> 00:53:32,679
What you want is those dynamics going, hey I'm a punch, then I'm gone, hey I'm a punch, then I'm gone.

1027
00:53:32,939 --> 00:53:36,881
And that tricks the player's ear into believing that there's more solid music happening in the background.

